@database MenuThing.guide

@node Main "MenuThing Main Help"
The main @{"MenuThing" link ABOUT} window consists of the following commands:

  @{" Edit Character Style " link CSTYLE} - Set custom character mappings.
  @{"    Edit Menu Sets    " link MSET} - Assign character styles to menu sets.
  @{"    Generate Menus    " link GEN} - Generate DLG custom menu files.

The following additional information is available:

  @{" Overview  " link OVERVIEW} - What the heck is MenuThing, anyway?
  @{" Tutorial  " link TUTORIAL} - Step by step instructions for MenuThing.
  @{" Planning  " link PLAN} - How to plan your menu sets before getting started.
  @{"Installing " link INSTALL} - How to install it on your computer.

  @{"   Blips   " link BLIP} - Describe the BLIP characters.
  @{" Languages " link LANG} - How to define menus with multiple languages.
  @{"    RIP    " link RIP} - Using RIP graphics.
  @{"Limitations" link LIMITS} - MenuThing can't do everything!

  @{"  Credits  " link CREDITS} - Acknowledgements.
  @{"   Legal   " link LEGAL} - Copyright and redistribution notice.
  @{" Giftware  " link ABOUT} - MenuThing is Giftware!
  @{"  History  " link HISTORY} - History of changes.
@endnode

@node OVERVIEW "Overview"
@{"MenuThing" link ABOUT} is a new kind of utility for DLG.  It's not a menu editor.
You still need to use DLG to create your menus and your menu sets.

Many DLG sysops have avoided the custom menus because of the
complicated %variables required.  MenuThing allows you to use your
favorite @{"ANSI paint program" link EDITOR} to design your custom menus in a WYSIWYG
(what you see is what you get) fashion.  You can now make all your menus
"smart menus" with no pain!

In its basic use, you can draw your menus in your ANSI paint
program the way you want them to appear to your BBS callers.  MenuThing
will generate the %codes for color changes so that they show up properly
for color and monochrome callers.

You can get more complex by defining @{"character styles" link CSTYLE}, which let you
maintain a single set of source files for your ASCII, IBM PC graphics,
Amiga ISO characters, and other styles.

To get started, look through the @{"tutorial" link TUTORIAL}.
@endnode

@node INSTALL "Installing it"

Create a directory called DOORS:MenuThing and place all the MenuThing
files there.

Alternately, you may want to install your files in some other place.
Create the directory, and then set the MENUTHING environment variable
to point at that directory.  Make sure you assign the MENUTHING
environment variable in your s:user-startup.  An example:

	setenv MENUTHING dlx:MThing

MenuThing requires AmigaDOS 2.04 or later.  You also must have an IBM
font in your FONTS: directory.  MenuThing will see which ones you have
and choose whichever one it likes best at the moment.
@endnode

@node TUTORIAL "Tutorial"
Let's turn your boring old main menu into a fancy one that will be the
talk of the town.

1.  @{"Plan" link PLAN} your menu sets.  This may be as simple as having an IBM set
    and an ASCII set, or it may be as complex as having a dozen menus
    set, each with a different language, IBM/ISO/ASCII styles, or RIP
    graphics.  For this tutorial, we will have menu set 1 be IBM PC
    graphics and menu set 2 be Amiga ISO graphics.

2.  Use the DLG SYSOP menu to create your Menu Sets.  You must do this
    in DLG, not here in MenuThing.

3.  Define your @{"character styles" link CSTYLE}.  MenuThing comes with
    several pre-defined character styles, so you may choose to use them
    rather than creating new styles.

4.  Use your favorite @{"ANSI editor" link EDITOR} to design your main menu.
    Make sure you use the @{"blip" link BLIP} symbols to exploit the full
    power of MenuThing!  If you're running low on ideas, look at the example
    menu supplied with MenuThing.  Save this file using the
    name MAIN.MTH (MTH indicates a MenuThing @{"source file" link SOURCE}).

5.  Tell MenuThing about your @{"menu sets" link MSET}.  For this tutorial,
    use these mappings:

        Menu set 0 - none
        Menu set 1 - basic IBM
        Menu set 2 - basic ISO

6.  Now you're ready for MenuThing to @{"generate" link GEN} your menus.
    It will create the files MAIN.NOV.1 and MAIN.NOV.2.  Take a look at
    them to see all the %variable codes it used.

7.  Copy the MAIN.NOV.1 and MAIN.NOV.2 files into your DLGconfig:menu
    directory.

8.  Login to DLG, select the Options command to change your menu set,
    and enjoy the results!
  
@endnode


@node PLAN "Planning Your Menu Sets"
The key to using MenuThing is to organize your menu sets and the associated
menu source files.  MenuThing can be a bit confusing until you understand
exactly how it decides what menus to generate.  If you do a small amount of
planning, MenuThing will do exactly what you want it to do.

This step-by-step guide to planning your menu sets assumes you are creating
your BBS from scratch.  If you already have several menu sets you may
discover you can create additional menu sets for specialized purposes with
almost no additional effort.  You may also be able to eliminate some of
your existing menu sets.

STEP 1.  Decide the major categories of menu sets you will have.  Most
         BBSs will only have one major category.  Examples of major
         categories would be different languages (English, French, etc.),
         different themes (Normal menus vs. Star Trek menus), or attempts
         to emulate different BBS software.

STEP 2.  Create a directory for each major category you decided upon in
         step 1.  You will place all the MenuThing source files in these
         these directories.  If you decide to add a new category in the
         future, simply create a new directory.

STEP 3.  Decide which character styles you will support on your BBS.  In
         essense, a character style represents a text font used by your
         caller's terminal program.  Most BBSs support plain ASCII and
         IBM ANSI, which are represented by the "Basic ASCII" and "Basic
	 IBM" character styles supplied with MenuThing.  The "Basic ISO"
         character style are for your users who use Amiga TOPAZ and similar
         ISO fonts.

STEP 4.  Use the DLG Sysop menus to create a CUSTOM MENU SET for each
         combination of major category and character style you wish to
         support.  For example, you might have:

		1. English, Plain ASCII
		2. Spanish, Plain ASCII
		3. English, IBM Graphics characters
		4. Spanish, IBM Graphics characters
		5. English, ISO characters
		6. Spanish, ISO characters
		7. Star Trek Theme, IBM Graphics

STEP 5.  Now, create your menu source for each of the major categories.
         Create MAIN.MTH, MSG_MAIN.MTH, FILE_MAIN.MTH, and other source
         files corresponding to your DLG menus.  Remember to keep the
         source in the directories you decided upon in step 2.

STEP 6.  Use MenuThing to define the input/output directories and
         character styles that are associated with each menu set.
	 Use the character style "None" for any menu set that you will
         be creating separately from MenuThing, such as RIP Graphics.

STEP 7.  You are now ready to have MenuThing generate your menus.
	 GENERATE ALL will do them all.  GENERATE ONE will generate
         all of the custom menus for ONE source file.
@endnode


@node LANG "Multiple Languages"
Suppose you want the following menu sets:

    Menu Set 1 = English IBM
    Menu Set 2 = English ASCII
    Menu Set 3 = French IBM
    Menu Set 4 = French ASCII

One way to manage this is to create separate directories for each
language.  Create an English directory and define all your MenuThing
English source files there.  Put all your French source files in another
directory.

Run MenuThing and set your @{"Menu Sets" link MSET} as follows:

    1. Menu Sets 1 and 3 use an IBM @{"character style" link CSTYLE}
    2. Menu Sets 2 and 4 use an ASCII @{"character style" link CSTYLE}
    3. Menu Sets 1 and 2 use the English @{"Input Path" link INPUT}
    4. Menu Sets 3 and 4 use the French @{"Input Path" link INPUT}
    5. All menu sets have the same @{"Output Path" link OUTPUT}

Now, @{"generate" link GEN} all your menus and MenuThing will sort through your
mess and generate the menus the way you want them.
@endnode

@node RIP "RIP Graphics"
MenuThing does not specifically support RIP graphics.  However, it
should be possible to use RIP in conjunction with MenuThing.

Suppose you want menu set 5 to be your RIP Graphics menus.  Use
whatever RIP drawing tools you have to create your RIP menus, and
name them appropriatly for menu set 5.

In MenuThing, define menu set 5 as "None" for its character
style.  This tells MenuThing to not generate any menus for menu
set 5.
@endnode

@node LIMITS "Limitations"

 · MenuThing only generates NOVICE menus in this release.  A future
   release may address the other levels of menus.

 · Mark uses an IBM ANSI picture in his main menu that does not easily
   translate into ASCII or AMIGA ANSI, but wants to use MenuThing to
   generate all his menus for ASCII, IBM, and AMIGA ISO.  To see how we
   solved this problem, see @{"The Penguin Problem" link PENGUIN}.

 · When parsing the blips for smart menus, MenuThing tries to guess which
   key is the command key.  To see what MenuThing can and cannot recognize,
   see @{"Command Key Recognition" link KEYS}.

 · To preserve the WYSIWYG editing, the blips for smart menus are converted
   to spaces in the output.  This means you cannot have a smart menu item
   that is not surrounded by spaces.  I plan to provide some alternate blips
   in a future release to handle this.

 · You cannot use the blip characters themselves as ANSI graphics.  For
   example, you cannot have a *.mth file with the IBM alpha and beta
   characters because MenuThing will try to parse them as blips.

 · Sometimes MenuThing seems to change the colors of smart menus.  In
   general, you should make the blip character be the same color as the
   first character in the following menu text.  The menu text will then
   be displayed in the color you expect.
@endnode

@node PENGUIN "The Penguin Problem"
MenuThing should be able to organize most of your menus, but it cannot
do everything.  When I started the project I knew it would not work for
everybody, and the beta testing confirmed my suspicions.  However, with
some understanding of how MenuThing generates its menus, you may be able
to get it to work.

Here is a true-life example.  Mark's BBS has three menu sets: 1=ASCII,
2=IBM ANSI, 3=AMIGA ISO.  He has one set of *.mth files for all of
his menus, and generates all three menu sets from this single set of
*.mth sources.  There is one exception, however.  Mark's Main Menu has
an ANSI picture of a penguin for his IBM ANSI callers, but a more
straightforward text menu for ASCII and AMIGA ISO.  How the heck does
Mark use MenuThing to do this?

Here is one technique: Create two input directories, "normal" and
"penguin", and a directory "result" to hold the generated menus.  Copy
all of the *.mth files into BOTH directories, with the only difference
being that the main.mth file is different in each one.  Setup your
menu sets in MenuThing as follows:

     Set  Input   Output   Char Style
     ---  -----   ------   ----------
      1   normal  result   Basic ASCII
      2   penguin result   Basic IBM
      3   normal  result   Basic ISO

Your menus will be generated properly.  Unfortunately, you must keep
two copies (or links) of the *.mth files.  If you don't keep the multiple
copies, you will not get all of the menus generated for one or more of
the menu sets.

A second solution is possible that only requires one copy of the source,
but requires multiple steps to generate the menus.  Put all *.mth source
files in the "normal" directory, and put ONLY the penguin main.mth in
the "penguin" directory.

Step 1, set all the input directories to "normal" and do a "Generate All".
This generates all the menus EXCEPT for the penguin menu.  Step 2, change
the menu set 2 input directory to be "penguin" and send its output to
RAM:.  Now, do a "Generate One Menu" and select the penguin/main.mth file.
This generates penguin main menus for all your menu sets, but puts them
in RAM:.  Since you only want main.nov.2, copy that file only into your
"result" directory.

There are other similar ways to get the menus generated the way you want,
but none of them are ideal.  A future version of MenuThing may address
these needs in an easier manner.

@endnode

@node KEYS "Command Key Recognition"
MenuThing reads your input source and makes an intelligent guess as to
which character is the command key for the menu item.  If you use the
correct @{"blip" link BLIP}, MenuThing will search for the key at the left or the
right of your menu text.

Most of the common styles of BBS menus are recognized by MenuThing.
For example, all of the following menu entries will be recognized as
the command letter "F":

   [F] Files      F-Files       Files [F]     Files=F
   <F> Files      f-files       Files <f>
   (F) Files      F Files       
   [f] files      f files       Many similar constructs
   <f>iles        F> files      are recognized.
   (f)iles        F. Files

Any ANSI sequences may be interspersed with the menu text and
MenuThing will read them correctly.  Therefore you may have the
brackets be a different color than the command key.

MenuThing also recognizes {F}, but the curly braces are special to
DLG and it may not be possible to create a menu in this format.

The following styles are not currently recognized by MenuThing:

   [ F ] Files            MenuThing thinks "[" is the command key
   < F > Files            MenuThing thinks "<" is the command key
   ( F ) Files            MenuThing thinks "(" is the command key
   Press <F> for files    MenuThing thinks "P" is the command key
   All[f]iles             MenuThing thinks "A" is the command key

MenuThing DOES recognize a bracket character surrounded by other
styles of brackets.  For example, "[<]" and "[>]" are parsed correctly.
However, "<<>" and "<>>" will cause a wrong guess, even if the command
character is in a different color.

@endnode

@node CSTYLE "Edit Character Style"
Character styles are one way to maintain several nearly-identical menus
using a single source.

 EXAMPLE:  You can draw IBM boxes in your menus.  Callers with an IBM
           graphics set will see your boxes, but what about callers who
           use ASCII or even Amiga Topaz?  MenuThing will
           make them look like box 1 shown at
           right.  What?  You like the box 2   +-------+  /-------\
           style instead?  No problem, just    | box 1 |  | box 2 |
           redefine the corner characters.     +-------+  \-------/

The basic idea of a character set is that it *translates* your IBM graphics
menus into other fonts.  For every possible character, you choose what the
user will see.

To get started, you should @{"Load" link LOADSTYLE} one of the pre-defined
character styles supplied with MenuThing.  Character styles are
kept in the Doors:MenuThing directory, and must be named #?.style.

All 256 possible characters are displayed in the main window.  For each
character, its hex value is shown in inverse video, followed by two
display characters.  Example:

    41 AA   This tells MenuThing that you want the hex value 41 (letter A)
            to be translated to letter A.  Big deal <<yawn>>

    42 BX   This tells MenuThing that you want the hex value 42 (letter B)
            to be translated to letter X.  Yuck.  Why would anybody want
            to do that?  More likely you will want to translate various
            graphics characters, like those IBM box edges and corners.

To change a @{"mapping" link MAP} click on the character you want to change.

Note that the "from" character is always shown in the IBM graphics font.
That's because you will be using those characters in your ANSI drawing
program when you design your menus.  The "to" characters are shown in
the @{"font" link FONT} that you choose for this character style.
@endnode

@node LOADSTYLE "Load Character Style"
Character styles are stored in files with the #?.style naming convention.
Several default styles are supplied with MenuThing:

   Basic_IBM.style    Use this for any IBM graphics menu set.

   Basic_ISO.style    Use this for ISO fonts such as Amiga Topaz.
                      IBM lines are converted to |-+= characters,
                      and some of the other IBM graphics characters
                      are translated to similar ISO characters.

   Basic_ASCII.style  Use this for non-graphical ASCII menu sets.
                      IBM lines are converted to |-+= characters,
                      and a few other translations are done.

If you modify these styles, you should save them as different names
so that you preserve the default styles.

If you come up with a better default ISO translation, or if you create
other styles that are of general interest, send them to me and I will
consider including them in the next release.
@endnode

@node FONT "Font Setting"
Each character style has an associated font used to view it.  You should
use a font similar to what your callers will be using.  For example, if
your callers are using an IBM font, use an IBM font for display.  If
your callers will use the native Amiga font, use topaz.

You could get really weird and define your own font.  Your callers would
have to download the font to see your weird menus.

NOTE: Currently only IBM and ISO (topaz) fonts are allowed.
@endnode

@node MAP "Character Mapping"
In the @{"Edit Character Style" link CSTYLE} window, click on a character to bring
up the Character Mapping window.

Use the slider to change the character translation.  The "from" character
is always shown using the IBM graphics font.  The "to" character is shown
using the font defined for this character style.

You can also type a character on the keyboard to set the "to" character.
Use RETURN for "ok" and ESC for "cancel" in this window only.
@endnode

@node MSET "Edit Menu Sets"
This window is where you define all the attributes of a Menu Set.
All of the menu sets you have defined in DLG will appear in the
list at the upper right.  Choose the menu set you want to work
with, then make any changes in the other gadgets.

Note: Menu Set 0 is the default green-and-white DLG menus.  If you want
to keep Menu Set 0 this way, define its character style as "None".

Any changes you make are saved to the file MenuThing.STUFF when you
click on OK.

To create a new menu set, you first must create it in the DLG sysop
menu.  Then, enter this window and your new menu set will be here.

@{"Character Style" link CSTYLE} lets you define which character style is to be
associated with this menu set.  If you choose "None", MenuThing will not
generate any custom menus for this particular menu set.

@{"Input Path" link INPUT} tells MenuThing where to find your MenuThing @{"source files" link SOURCE}.
You will probably want to keep all your source files in a single directory,
or you may want to group your source files if you use different foreign
@{"languages" link LANG} or radically different styles.

@{"Output Path" link OUTPUT} tells MenuThing where to write the @{"custom menu files" link CUSTOM}
that it generates.  If you set this to DLGconfig:menus it will overwrite
your current custom menu files.  If you set it to some other directory,
you will have to manually copy the generated custom menu files into
DLGconfig:menus to allow DLG to find them.

@{"Allow Background Colors" link BACK} tells MenuThing whether or not to write background
color changes in the output file.  DLG currently does not provide a %code
to change the background color, so use this at your own discretion.

@{"Reset ANSI sequence" link RESET} causes MenuThing to generate an ANSI reset
sequence at the beginning and end of the generated file.
@endnode

@node INPUT "Input Path"
Keep all your MenuThing source files in the Input Path directory.
Specify the Input Path using the @{"Menu Set" link MSET} window.

You must create this directory yourself.  MenuThing will not create it
for you.

This directory path is relative to the Doors:MenuThing directory.
@endnode

@node OUTPUT "Output Path"
MenuThing generates its output files to the Output Path directory.
Specify the Output Path using the @{"Menu Set" link MSET} window.

You must create this directory yourself.  MenuThing will not create it
for you.

This directory path is relative to the Doors:MenuThing directory.
@endnode

@node BACK "Allow Background Colors"
If your menu source contains ANSI background color changes (color code
40 through 47), by default MenuThing will ignore them because DLG
does not provide any %codes to represent them.

If you turn on this option, MenuThing will insert the actual ANSI
color changes into the custom menu output.  Do this only if you
need background colors AND you do not care that it does not work
properly if the user has ANSI color disabled.

Proper use of this option is to have separate menu sets for color
and monochrome users.  Turn this option ON for the color set and
OFF for the monochrome set.  If DLG ever provides %codes for background
colors, this option will not be necessary.
@endnode

@node RESET "Reset ANSI sequence"

This option causes MenuThing to place a %ao code at the beginning and
end of the custom menus.  You might want to do this if your ANSI
screen painter does not do it automatically, or if you always forget
to do it yourself.

@endnode

@node BLIP "Blips - MenuThing Directives"
A "blip" is an IBM graphics character that MenuThing treats as a
directive.  Place blips in your MenuThing source wherever you want
special treatment of the input file.  In most cases, the blips are
expanded into DLG %variables.  The output seen by the user will show
each blip replaced by a blank character.

When you first read the description of each blip, you might be wondering
why it is so complex.  Actually it is quite simple, and lets you create
your source menus in a WYSIWYG (what you see is what you get) manner.
You will quickly realize it is a thousand times easier to use the blips
than to try to use the DLG %variables directly.

Click @{"here" SYSTEM "doors:MenuThing/blips"} to view the MenuThing blips and their descriptions.
The blips use an IBM graphics font so they cannot be included directly
in this AmigaGuide file.
@endnode

@node GEN "Generate Menus"
After you have done all the other steps, you're ready for MenuThing
to actually generate your menus.  @{"Generate One Menu" link GENONE} will allow you
to specify a single menu to be generated.  @{"Generate All Menus" link GENALL} tells
MenuThing to generate all the menus that it knows about.
@endnode

@node GENONE "Generate One Menu"
When you click this gadget, a file requester will appear allowing you
to select a MenuThing @{"source file" link SOURCE}.  After selecting the source
file, MenuThing will generate the DLG custom menu for each menu set.

NOTE:  This command usually will generate MORE THAN ONE output menu.  It
processes one input menu source and generates ALL the custom menus for
each menu set that use that menu source.

Select this action after you have made a minor change to one menu.  It is
strongly encouraged that you login to DLG and verify that the generated
menus appear as you expect.

MenuThing knows which menus to generate by looking at the input
directory of the source file.  The source file you choose must be in
a valid input directory for one or more menu sets.
@endnode

@node GENALL "Generate All Menus"
This gadget does it all.  It will find every @{"source file" link SOURCE} in every
@{"input directory" link INPUT} and generate every custom menu file that you want.
You might want to do this after you have made a lot of changes to a
lot of menus.
@endnode

@node SOURCE "MenuThing Source Files"
You create your MenuThing source files with any @{"ANSI editor" link EDITOR}.  Make sure
your editor is using an IBM graphics font that displays all of the IBM PC
graphics characters.  MenuThing assigns meaning to specific graphics
characters.

MenuThing source files @{"must" link MUST} be named as *.MTH.  For example,
use the name MAIN.MTH for your main menu, MSG_MAIN.MTH for your message menu,
and FILE_MAIN.MTH for your file menu.

Generated custom menus will be named *.NOV.n, where n is the menu set
number.
@endnode

@node EDITOR "ANSI Editors"
Use any ANSI Editor of your choice to create your MenuThing source files.
I happen to use LaDraw, but there are several others available for the
Amiga, and many others on the IBM platform.

Here are some tips when creating your source files:

  - The ANSI Editor @{"must" link MUST} use an IBM PC graphics font.
    Otherwise you will get confused by the special codes.

  - Do NOT save your files with CLEAR SCREENS or ANSI SCREEN POSITIONING.

@endnode

@node MUST "Absolutely!"
Really!  You must be sure of this!
@endnode

@node CUSTOM "DLG Custom Menu Files"
In case you didn't know, a DLG custom menu is nothing more than a file
that is displayed to the user when they view a menu.

MenuThing creates DLG custom menu files.
@endnode

@node CREDITS "Acknowledgements"
Special thanks to the beta testers who gave me valuable feedback and
insight:  Brian Finley, Rick Lembree, Mark Montminy, Kevin Snider.

@{"MenuThing" link ABOUT} is loosely based on CyberANSI, a Xenolink program I wrote
many moons ago.  It used an ANSI paint program to create menus, and
generated ASCII and ANSI menus with embedded Xeno-codes.  The program
was hard-coded for my BBS and not customizable.  I released the source
to the Xeno community when I switched to DLG, but I never heard
whether anyone made any use of it.

Next came DANSI (DLG-ANSI).  I rewrote CyberANSI during my conversion
from Xenolink to DLG, making it more flexible and DLG-specific.  When
my DLG BBS went on-line on 31-Dec-1992, my ASCII, IBM ANSI, and AMIGA
ANSI menus were maintained using DANSI.  Similar to CyberANSI, it was
customizable only by changing the C code.

Shortly therafter I sent copies of the DANSI source to Mark Montminy
and Reid Bishop.  Mark modified it to generate his menus, while Reid
re-wrote it in FORTH, added a few features, and renamed it MkMenus.
For months Reid and I talked about collaborating on a fully-
customizable version, but we never found the time, nor were we able to
agree on what it would look like, much less what language it would be
written in!

Finally in July of 1993 I wanted to make a few changes to my menus
that DANSI couldn't handle.  Since EmacsDLG was finally in good shape,
I decided I had time to convert DANSI into a customizable menu thing.
The GUI front-end was created using GadToolsBox, with SAS/C 6.3 used
for the code.
@endnode

